This recipe is a great recipe for a cold weather dinner. It is pretty basic, I definitely added my spin. Here goes: I used all pieces of the chicken, not just thighs. I added garlic when I was sauteeing the onions, about 2 TBSP of Herbes de Provence, some fresh sage and a splash of wine to deglaze the pan. I let this all cook together a few minutes, then added the rest of the ingredients. I also added about 2 cups of chicken broth before I put it in the oven, as there wasn't enough liquid to cover the chicken. It baked and came out super tender, and super delicious! I only gave it three forks because I felt it needed a bit more zing added to it. (Gave it a shot of hot sauce in my bowl after serving) I will use this recipe again, putting my own spin on it each and every time!

Rating: 3
This recipe is a great jumping off point; the ingredients of this recipe seemed a little bland (and I actually loathe stewed tomatoes), so after reading several reviews I made a lot of changes which resulted in a delicious meal. I substituted boneless, skinless chicken breasts for thighs, and canned diced tomatoes for stewed; reduced onion to one, and added diced carrots to the onions. Then, I added about a teaspoon of crushed garlic and cooked until fragrant, added some white wine and cooked down until almost dry, before adding the tomatoes, along with about a teaspoon of bouquet garni (not being able to decide which herb would be best), simmered the tomato/onion/carrot/garlic mixture for a few minutes, added the beans, nestled the browned chicken breasts into the bean/tomato mix, and cooked on low heat, covered, on the stovetop, rather than the oven. I know that my version is quite different from the recipe as written, but it was really good, and I will definitely make it again. The bouquet garni is a nice mix of various herbs, nothing too overpowering, but gave the beans a good flavor. I had a chicken with bean dish at a pub/restaurant in Vancouver recently, which gave me the idea for chicken and beans in the first place, but knew that just cooking chicken, beans, onions and tomatoes would not be enough. I think that there is a lot of room for creativity in this recipe and I would not hesitate to vary the ingredients depending on individual preferences as well as what is available.

