Rating: 2
I agree that this receipe can be greatly improved by adding the following: Add 2-3 cloves of chopped garlic along with a tablespoon of fresh minced rosemary (or a teaspoon of dried, crumbled) a couple of minutes after starting to fry the onions. After adding the beans, add a cup of low-salt chicken broth (Swansons is best!) and simmer for one hour, covered, to allow beans to soften and the flavors to meld. Then add chicken as the recipe states. This produced a kind of "chicken cassoulet" that's yummy. I served it with steamed haricots verts.

Rating: 3
This is a good recipe, but very basic. If you really want to make this dish sing and dance, add some persillade (chopped garlic minced with flat-leaf parsley), grated lemon rind, and one or two minced anchovy fillet before it goes in the oven

Rating: 3
I was suprised at how good this was. I made as written, except removed the skin from the thighs. Also, one medium onion was enough for the recipe's 1 & 1/2 cup. I used great northern beans. I will try with turkey bacon next time to make it lower in fat, but would recommend you make it with real bacon the first time. The smokey flavor from the bacon was pretty important to the overall taste.

Rating: 3
